<br>
Flacon returns to his closet and shuts the door. Standing rock still, he simply stares at the small mat upon the floor. Nodding to himself, his right foot strikes out and kicks the mat away. Falling to his knees, he gently removes the loose floor stone, and retrieves a bone scroll case. Replacing the stone, Flacon starts to pack his things. Only the essentials. He knows that this day is the start of a long journey, with an unknown destination. After several minutes of securing provisions and supplies, the Sickly gnome bonedancer stands ready. <br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Whatever happens next, Bertoxxulous guide me.&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
Resolute in his determination to solve this mystery, he turns and opens the door. He heads straight for Kerridwynn's office. Standing outside her door, he hesitates for only a second before knocking<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Tis me M'lady..&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> <br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Kerridwynn opens the door, stepping aside to let the sickly necromancer in. The fire in the hearth is blazing with indigo flames, casting somewhat eerie lighting about the office. Kerridwynn motions to a chair before her desk, and then walks around the desk and seats herself. She clasps her hands together and rests her chin upon them, looking at Flacon.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Let's see what you have.&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The sickly gnome took a seat, placing his pack and travelling supplies near the door. In his hand he held a bone scroll case. There were no markings of any kind on the case. Flacon took a deep breath as Kerridwynn sat down, and began to speak..<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;As I'm sure you are aware, Eonis Mournunder is the head of my order in the Mines of Malfunction. Soon after I decided on my path, I asked Eonis about my parents, and how I came to live in the Mines. He refused to speak to me at that time, saying only that my surname was Vex, and that I should keep that closer to me than any other secret I held dear. I spent months trying to discover what he meant by that, and my investigation lead me to the great library of Neriak. It was here that I was able to find a reference regarding this surname. It mentions a Gnome Shadowknight named Binuven Vex, who studied the ancient evils created by Avhi Escron. It seems Binuven was sacrificed by the spirt of Avhi herself in a dark ritual to Bertoxxulous, but not before he had a son, named Llaorn. I believe that this Llaorn is my actual birth father.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Flacon pauses a moment and takes a sip of the brandy before him.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Inside this scroll case, is a charge written by this Llaorn Vex, to Eonis Mournunder.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Flacon picks up the case and begins to unscrew the cap. Without warning, a spectral hand reaches out of nothingness behind him and rests upon the gnomes shoulder. In an instant, both the hand and the sickly gnome are gone. Left behind on the chair and floor are Flacon's personal items and robes. The scroll case clatters to the floor where it comes to rest at Kerridwynn's feet<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Almost immediately after the eyes closed, they opened again, this time inside a small closet in the Hall of the ones called the Harvesters. It took a mere split second for the eyes to see that it wasn't here. Slowly rotating, it sensed the flesh was nearby. Locking on to it's location, the eyes closed. The flesh was in the presence of a Teir' Dal female. Keeping it's eyes closed it reached out of the spectral vortex with a clawed, bony hand and placed it upon the shoulder of the gnome. Instantly the gnomes corporal body was transported into the vortex, along with the eyes. The Teir' Dal Female watched in amazement as the gnome appeared to simply vanish, personal affects and clothing falling to the floor.<br>
<br>
Inside the vortex, the eyes bore into its captives' with hatred. All the while, Flacon merely screamed in absolute agony.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Our destinies await Flacon&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Kerridwynn's eyes widen as the gnome disappears from right before her. She blinks, then her eyes narrow. She bends down to pick up the scrollcase.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;What in the name of the seven hells is in this?&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
Kerridwynn moves towards the doorway, studying to floor and the air about the place where Flacon disappeared, leery of any sudden movements or appearances. The words of a blessing against the undead rest on her lips.<br>
<br>
Nothing moves, or stops her, and she reaches the door. Opening it, she moves purposefully towards the main hall. She was going to need some help.<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Never before had the sickly gnome imagined such pain, such anguish, let <br>
alone felt it. Wave after relentless wave, like a winter storm upon a rocky <br>
beach, the agony washed over him again, and again, and again. Rising and <br>
falling, swelling and cresting, wave after wave. <br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Stop!..... enough!.......... &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
Flacon's Captor, now visable as a spectral Gnome in phantom plate laughed <br>
at the bonedancer.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;It never stops. It's never enough. Soon you will know.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Waves crashing against a stone beach. Agony assaulting the very fiber of <br>
his existence. Rising and falling, and always the screaming. Flacon could <br>
feel his soul tear from the screaming, as if a wolf were eating at him from <br>
the inside. The taste of blood at the back of his throat as it began to <br>
well from his erupted vocal cords. And yet he screamed. Unconciousness, it <br>
seemed, would not come. It would not come and take the pain away. And <br>
still his captor laughed.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Enough.&quot; Came a voice from nowhere.<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
