<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;I'm not finished with you, either&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Said Binuven, before disappearing back into the void<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
There was a soft tearing sound outside the main doors of the hall. It sounded like a piece of the finest silk slowly being torn in two. It was followed almost immediately by a hard packing Slap, as the lifeless body of Flacon fell to the gutter. The only other sound was a faint spectral voice.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;I'm not finished with you, either&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
The gnome's body was naked with black blood crusted around his mouth and chest. His sightless eyes were wide open, eyeballs protruding, his face a rictus of primal agony. In the center of his chest were five small cresent shaped wounds that weeped a foul smelling and putrid liquid. Nothing in the streets would go near the lump of meat, not even the rats.<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Kerridwynn stepped out of the front door of Harvester Hall on her way to the nightly hunt. Her nose wrinkled at an undescribable stench, and she quickly looked about for the origin of the offending odour. <br>
<br>
Peering into the darkness, she walked down the steps, scanning the ground. Ahead, she saw a pale shape marred by bits of blackness. As she walked towards it, the smell grew stronger until she had to hold a hand over her nose and breath shallowly through her mouth.<br>
<br>
Kerridwynn drew close enough to recognize the body as that of Flacon, the gnome necromancer. Turning abruptly, Kerridwynn fell to her knees, her stomach rebelling. Her eyes shut tightly, she retched into the gutter until her stomach was empty.<br>
<br>
Composing herself, she turned back to the body. She could tell by looking at it that the sickly little gnome was dead. The question was...could he be resurrected?<br>
<br>
Kerrdiwynn stood, and began to chant the words of renewal and rebirth her kind was known for.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Innoruuk, grant me strength that I may raise this servant of the dark gods...&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> <br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
For what seemed like an eternity, the Gnome sat in darkness. Oblivion was his only reality. He was aware of his minds thoughts, and nothing more. His did not know if his senses had failed him, or if there was nothing around him to sense. In reality, he had been cut off from the tie to his corporal body. The ordeal in the Ruins of Lxanvom had severed the link between mind and body. Now, as his Mistress Kerridwynn began her prayers to Innoruuk, Flacon sensed a slight movement in the nothingness around him. Like a tidal wave, his senses came flooding back, pain being the first, but even that was short lived under the prayers of his mistress. Within moments his body and mind where whole, his pain and sickly hue, gone. All that remained to show testament to his ordeal where the five cresent shaped wounds on his chest. Those would never fully heal.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;M'lady...&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Flacon croaked.<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Kerridwynn smiled with relief at hearing Flacon's voice, and she quickly knelt down next to him. Laying her hands upon him, she allowed a bit of power to channel through her into him, healing his wounds. She eyed the wounds on his chest with a bit of alarm, but pushed that aside after a moment's thought. Those wounds looked like the kind that would stay around as a reminder...like her hands.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Flacon...thank the Fates. Let's get you inside the hall.&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
Kerridwynn helped the gnome to rise, and together they walked slowly back into Harvester Hall.<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
For several days, Flacon rested in silence inside his closet. He refused to take the meals that were sent to him, and either ignored or did not hear the knocks on his door. The gnome reflected upon everything that had happened, and tried to put the pieces together. <br>
<br>
Avhi, one of the most powerful necromancers of all time, had returned to Norrath and destroyed the gnome Shadowknight know as Binuven when he successfully duplicated some of her forbidden research. She in turn enslaved his spirit and together they now serve in the realm of Bertoxxulous himself. Before Binuven was destroyed however he passed along the plague to someone known as Llaorn Vex. <br>
<br>
That sickness, Avhi's &quot;greatest gift to the world&quot; had somehow been passed on to Flacon. Now, as he sat upon his bedroll, he realized that the sickness he had all his life was no longer there. The sickly gnome, was sickly no longer. In its place where five small cresent shaped wounds upon his chest. To anyone observing the wounds, it appeared as if someone with exceptional long and sharp finger nails had driven them into the gnomes chest. In fact, this wasn't far from the truth. Avhi had plunged her incorporal hand into Flacon's flesh and had siphoned her &quot;gift&quot; from his flesh. The wounds would never fully heal, a weeping reminder years from now of his time in the ruins. <br>
<br>
The ordeal had killed the gnome, and had actually severed the link between his body and mind for a brief period of time. The effect of which was very dramatic. The gnome now saw the corporeal world with new eyes, and new understanding. Now, he realized that death truly was only the beginning, and that in order to make others understand, he must send them to thier deaths. It was his duty, his responsiblity to Bertoxxulous, to make the world understand. There would no longer be any division. Good, evil, neutral... all must die, as he had. <br>
<br>
Flacon rose to his feet, and retrived his vault notes. He would need to retrive his savings. A new prespective on life, and death, required a dramatic change at every possible level.<br>
<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;Some new clothes will do for a start.&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<br>
Half naked, the gnome headed out to buy new supplies. Today was the first day, of the rest of his life.<br>
